Namespace prefix consistency (all symbols must start with `package-name-`)\n- Dependency declarations match actual `require` calls\n- Use of deprecated APIs\n- License header presence\n\n---\n\n## 1c. checkdoc (Built-in)\n\nValidates Emacs Lisp docstrings against the Emacs coding conventions (capitalization, punctuation, argument references in UPPER CASE, first line as a complete sentence, etc.).\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  --eval \"(checkdoc-file \\\"file.el\\\")\" \\\n  --kill\n```\n\n**Better batch wrapper (exits non-zero on findings):**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  --eval '\n  (let ((sentence-end-double-space nil))\n    (checkdoc-file \"file.el\")\n    (when (get-buffer \"*Warnings*\")\n      (kill-emacs 1)))' \n```\n\n**With Eask:**\n```bash\neask lint checkdoc file.el\n```\n\n**Nix:** Built into Emacs, no extra package needed.\n\n---\n\n## 1d. elint (Built-in)\n\nPerforms static analysis for unresolved functions and variables. Less commonly used than byte-compile but catches different issues.\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  --eval '(elint-file \"file.el\")' \\\n  --kill\n```\n\n**Nix:** Built into Emacs.\n\n---\n\n## 1e. relint\n\nLints regular expressions in Emacs Lisp code. Catches common regexp mistakes, redundant constructs, and potential bugs.\n\n**Repository:** https://github.com/mattiase/relint\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  -l relint.el \\\n  --eval '(relint-batch \"file.el\")' \\\n  --kill\n```\n\n**With Eask:**\n```bash\neask lint regexps file.el\n```\n\n**Nix:**\n```nix\npkgs.emacsPackages.relint\n```\n\n---\n\n## 1f. elisp-lint (Aggregator)\n\nA wrapper that combines multiple linters (byte-compile, checkdoc, package-lint, indent checks) into a single batch command. Very popular in CI.\n\n**Repository:** https://github.com/gonewest818/elisp-lint\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  -l elisp-lint.el \\\n  -f elisp-lint-files-batch \\\n  file.el\n```\n\n**Configurable via `.dir-locals.el`** or command-line flags to enable/disable specific checks (checkdoc, package-lint, indent, fill-column, etc.).\n\n**Nix:**\n```nix\npkgs.emacsPackages.elisp-lint\n```\n\n---\n\n## 1g. melpazoid\n\nUsed by MELPA itself during package review. The strictest linter -- useful if you intend to submit packages.\n\n**Repository:** https://github.com/riscy/melpazoid\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\npython melpazoid/melpazoid.py --local file.el\n```\n\n**Nix:** Not packaged; clone the repo and use Python.\n\n---\n\n## Linting Summary Table\n\n| Tool | Scope | Batch Mode | Nix Package |\n|------|-------|------------|-------------|\n| byte-compile | Compilation errors/warnings | Built-in | `pkgs.emacs` |\n| package-lint | Package conventions | Yes | `emacsPackages.package-lint` |\n| checkdoc | Docstring conventions | Built-in | `pkgs.emacs` |\n| elint | Static analysis | Built-in | `pkgs.emacs` |\n| relint | Regular expressions | Yes | `emacsPackages.relint` |\n| elisp-lint | Aggregator | Yes | `emacsPackages.elisp-lint` |\n\n---\n\n# 2. FORMATTING\n\nThere is **no universally adopted `gofmt`-equivalent** for Emacs Lisp. The Emacs Lisp community has historically relied on Emacs's own indentation engine (`indent-region`) as the canonical formatter. However, several tools exist:\n\n## 2a. Emacs Built-in indent-region (De Facto Standard)\n\nThe closest thing to a canonical formatter. Emacs's own Lisp indentation engine is what virtually all Elisp developers use. It can be run in batch mode.\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch file.el \\\n  --eval '(indent-region (point-min) (point-max))' \\\n  -f save-buffer\n```\n\n**Check-only mode (for CI, detect unformatted code):**\n```bash\nemacs -batch file.el \\\n  --eval '\n  (let ((original (buffer-string)))\n    (indent-region (point-min) (point-max))\n    (unless (string= original (buffer-string))\n      (message \"File %s is not properly indented\" buffer-file-name)\n      (kill-emacs 1)))'\n```\n\n**Nix:** Built into Emacs.\n\n**Limitation:** Only handles indentation, not whitespace normalization, line breaking, or alignment.\n\n---\n\n## 2b. elisp-autofmt\n\nA more comprehensive formatter that goes beyond indentation. Handles indentation, line length, and some structural formatting.\n\n**Repository:** https://codeberg.org/ideasman42/emacs-elisp-autofmt\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  -l elisp-autofmt.el \\\n  --eval '(elisp-autofmt-file \"file.el\")'\n```\n\n**Nix:** Not in nixpkgs as of my last knowledge (you may need to package it yourself or use a Nix flake overlay). You can install it manually:\n```bash\ngit clone https://codeberg.org/ideasman42/emacs-elisp-autofmt.git\n```\n\n**Features:**\n- Indentation normalization\n- Trailing whitespace removal\n- Line-length–aware formatting\n- Preserves intentional formatting via comments\n\n---\n\n## 2c. lisp-format\n\nA command-line Lisp formatter that works across Common Lisp, Scheme, and Emacs Lisp.\n\n**Repository:** https://github.com/eschulte/lisp-format\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nlisp-format file.el\n```\n\n**Nix:** Not in nixpkgs; install from source.\n\n**Note:** Less Elisp-specific than `elisp-autofmt`; uses generic Lisp heuristics.\n\n---\n\n## 2d. Practical Recommendation\n\nFor CI, the most reliable approach is:\n\n```bash\n# Check that all .el files are properly indented by Emacs's own engine\nemacs -batch \\\n  --eval '\n  (dolist (file command-line-args-left)\n    (find-file file)\n    (let ((original (buffer-string)))\n      (indent-region (point-min) (point-max))\n      (unless (string= original (buffer-string))\n        (message \"Indentation mismatch in %s\" file)\n        (kill-emacs 1))))' \\\n  -- *.el\n```\n\nThis uses the same indentation engine every Elisp developer has, so it creates no adoption friction.\n\n---\n\n# 3. CODE COVERAGE\n\n## 3a. undercover.el (Primary Tool)\n\nThe main code coverage tool for Emacs Lisp. Instruments code, runs ERT tests, and generates coverage reports. Integrates with Coveralls, Codecov, and local LCOV/SimpleCov output.\n\n**Repository:** https://github.com/undercover-el/undercover.el\n\n**Installation via Nix:**\n```nix\npkgs.emacsPackages.undercover\n```\n\n**Setup in test file:**\n```elisp\n;;; my-package-test.el --- Tests -*- lexical-binding: t; -*-\n\n(require 'undercover)\n(undercover \"my-package.el\"\n  (:report-format 'lcov)       ;; or 'text, 'codecov\n  (:report-file \"coverage.lcov\")\n  (:send-report nil))           ;; set to t for CI services\n\n(require 'my-package)\n(require 'ert)\n\n;; ... tests ...\n```\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  -L . \\\n  -l my-package-test.el \\\n  -f ert-run-tests-batch-and-exit\n```\n\nThe coverage report is written to the file specified by `:report-file`.\n\n**CI Integration (Coveralls/Codecov):**\n```elisp\n(undercover \"my-package.el\"\n  (:report-format 'codecov)\n  (:send-report t))  ;; Automatically sends to Codecov/Coveralls\n```\n\nEnvironment variables `COVERALLS_REPO_TOKEN` or `CODECOV_TOKEN` must be set.\n\n**With Eask:**\n```bash\neask install-deps --dev\neask test ert my-package-test.el\n```\n\n(Add `undercover` to your Eask file's `(depends-on \"undercover\")` in the development section.)\n\n**How it works:** Uses Emacs's built-in `edebug` instrumentation to track which forms are evaluated during test execution.\n\n---\n\n## 3b. testcover.el (Built-in, Limited)\n\nEmacs ships with `testcover.el`, which provides a simpler coverage mechanism. It is primarily designed for interactive use (highlights uncovered code in a buffer) and does not produce CI-friendly reports.\n\n**Run interactively:**\n```elisp\n(require 'testcover)\n(testcover-start \"my-package.el\")\n;; Run your tests\n(testcover-mark-all \"my-package.el\")\n;; Covered lines are highlighted\n```\n\n**Batch mode is awkward** -- no standard report format. Use `undercover.el` instead for CI.\n\n**Nix:** Built into Emacs.\n\n---\n\n## Coverage Summary\n\n| Tool | Report Formats | CI Integration | Nix Package |\n|------|---------------|----------------|-------------|\n| undercover.el | LCOV, Codecov, Coveralls, text | Yes (Coveralls, Codecov) | `emacsPackages.undercover` |\n| testcover.el | Interactive highlighting only | No | Built-in |\n\n---\n\n# 4. PERFORMANCE PROFILING\n\n## 4a. benchmark-run (Built-in)\n\nThe simplest benchmarking tool. Measures elapsed time, GC count, and GC time for an expression.\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  --eval '\n  (message \"%S\"\n    (benchmark-run 1000\n      (your-function-here)))'\n```\n\nReturns `(ELAPSED-TIME GC-COUNT GC-TIME)`.\n\n**Variant with repetition reporting:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  -l benchmark \\\n  --eval '(message \"%s\" (benchmark 1000 (form-to-test)))'\n```\n\n**Nix:** Built into Emacs (`benchmark.el` is part of core).\n\n---\n\n## 4b. elp (Emacs Lisp Profiler, Built-in)\n\nFunction-level profiler. Instruments specific functions and reports call counts, total time, and average time.\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  -L . \\\n  -l my-package.el \\\n  --eval '\n  (require (quote elp))\n  (elp-instrument-package \"my-package\")\n  ;; Run your workload\n  (my-package-do-something)\n  (elp-results)'\n```\n\n**Output format (printed to stdout in batch mode):**\n```\nFunction Name          Call Count  Elapsed Time  Average Time\nmy-package-parse       1000        0.523         0.000523\nmy-package-transform   500         1.204         0.002408\n```\n\n**Nix:** Built into Emacs.\n\n---\n\n## 4c. profiler.el (Built-in, Emacs 24.3+)\n\nA sampling profiler (like `perf` or `dtrace`). Captures CPU and memory profiles by periodic sampling. Better than `elp` for finding unexpected hotspots because it does not require you to pre-select functions.\n\n**Run from command line:**\n```bash\nemacs -batch \\\n  -L . \\\n  -l my-package.el \\\n  --eval '\n  (profiler-start (quote cpu+mem))\n  ;; Run your workload\n  (my-package-heavy-operation)\n  (profiler-stop)\n  (profiler-report)\n  (profiler-report-write-profile \"profile-output.txt\")'\n```\n\n**Interactive use** is more common -- `M-x profiler-start`, run workload, `M-x profiler-report` gives a tree view of CPU/memory hotspots.\n\n**Nix:** Built into Emacs.\n\n---\n\n## 4d. benchmark-init (Startup Profiling)\n\nSpecifically designed to profile Emacs startup/init time. Less relevant for library development but useful for configuration optimization.\n\n**Repository:** https://github.com/dholm/benchmark-init-el\n\n**Nix:**\n```nix\npkgs.emacsPackages.benchmark-init\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4e. Practical Batch Benchmarking Script\n\nHere is a reusable pattern for CI-integrated benchmarking:\n\n```bash\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# bench.sh -- Benchmark an Elisp function in batch mode\n\nemacs -batch \\\n  -L . \\\n  -l my-package.el \\\n  --eval \"\n(require 'benchmark)\n\n(let* ((iterations 10000)\n       (result (benchmark-run iterations\n                 (my-package-function test-input)))\n       (elapsed (car result))\n       (gc-count (cadr result))\n       (gc-time (caddr result)))\n  (message \\\"Iterations: %d\\\" iterations)\n  (message \\\"Total time: %.4f sec\\\" elapsed)\n  (message \\\"Per iteration: %.6f sec\\\" (/ elapsed iterations))\n  (message \\\"GC runs: %d (%.4f sec)\\\" gc-count gc-time)\n  (message \\\"Time minus GC: %.4f sec\\\" (- elapsed gc-time)))\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Profiling Summary\n\n| Tool | Type | Batch Mode | What It Measures | Nix Package |\n|------|------|------------|------------------|-------------|\n| benchmark-run | Micro-benchmark | Yes | Wall time, GC for a single form | Built-in |\n| elp | Instrumenting profiler | Yes | Per-function call count and time | Built-in |\n| profiler.el | Sampling profiler | Yes | CPU and memory hotspots (tree) | Built-in |\n| benchmark-init | Startup profiler | Partial | Init-file load times | `emacsPackages.benchmark-init` |\n\n---\n\n# Recommended CI Pipeline\n\nPutting it all together, here is what a comprehensive Elisp CI configuration looks like:\n\n```yaml\n# Example GitHub Actions workflow\nsteps:\n  - name: Lint (byte-compile)\n    run: emacs -batch -L . --eval \"(setq byte-compile-error-on-warn t)\" -f batch-byte-compile *.el\n\n  - name: Lint (package-lint)\n    run: emacs -batch -l package-lint -f package-lint-batch-and-exit my-package.el\n\n  - name: Lint (checkdoc)\n    run: |\n      emacs -batch --eval '\n        (let ((files (directory-files \".\" nil \"\\\\.el$\")))\n          (dolist (f files)\n            (checkdoc-file f)))'\n\n  - name: Lint (relint)\n    run: emacs -batch -l relint --eval '(relint-batch \"my-package.el\")'\n\n  - name: Check indentation\n    run: |\n      emacs -batch my-package.el --eval '\n        (let ((orig (buffer-string)))\n          (indent-region (point-min) (point-max))\n          (unless (string= orig (buffer-string))\n            (kill-emacs 1)))'\n\n  - name: Test with coverage\n    run: emacs -batch -L . -l my-package-test.el -f ert-run-tests-batch-and-exit\n\n  - name: Upload coverage\n    uses: codecov/codecov-action@v3\n    with:\n      file: coverage.lcov\n```\n\n---\n\n# Nix Quick Reference\n\nFor a development shell with all the tools:\n\n```nix\n# shell.nix\n{ pkgs ? import <nixpkgs> {} }:\n\nlet\n  emacsWithPackages = pkgs.emacs.pkgs.withPackages (epkgs: [\n    epkgs.package-lint\n    epkgs.relint\n    epkgs.elisp-lint\n    epkgs.undercover\n    epkgs.benchmark-init\n  ]);\nin pkgs.mkShell {\n  buildInputs = [ emacsWithPackages ];\n}\n```\n\nThen run `nix-shell` to enter a shell with Emacs and all linting/coverage tools available.\n\n---\n\n**Note:** The Perplexity search API was unavailable during this research, so all information above is based on my training data through May 2025. The tools listed are well-established and stable; however, I recommend checking the respective GitHub repositories for any updates released after that 